The structure of this code is a bit fragile. You have a host of arrays that all "magically" line up. In case of an error, zero values are added to all arrays, otherwise scores are added to all arrays. There might be corner cases where, in one iteration of this loop https://github.com/vidAio-subnet/vidaio-subnet/blob/574f8ae2b26f3b9534cdb715842a62e6d250c73b/services/scoring/server.py#L379 more than one item is added to the scoring arrays for one input item. E.g. if `dist_cap.release()` or `ref_cap.release()` or `os.unlink()` raises an exception, the code just added zeroes, and then adds another set of zeroes. I'm not saying this is the case, but it is a way how the alignment between arrays `request.content_lengths` and `length_scores` may be off. There are even more subtle misalignments possible, in case the outer `except:` clause is run after `vmaf_scores.append()` is executed, e.g. when `dist_cap.read()` raises an exception, or likewise when one of the `calculate_...()` functions raises an exception.

The way I would write this, to prevent such issues, is by either using dicts, or indexed arrays (typically numpy arrays). In both cases you would be able to set/update e.g. `scores[miner_uid]`, leaving no room for ambiguity as to who/what is being updated.

Even if the current code has no such issue, the code is fragile in the sense that any change to it may lead to such issue, especially in the context of adversarial miners, that (for their particular reasons) may decide to trigger an issue.

To lazily fix the code in its current form, I'd work toward a structure where there is only one set of `.append()` calls, which is guaranteed to execute once per iteration. For clarity the for loop may simply call a subroutine that handles one item per invocation, ending in either "return 0,0,0,0,0" or "return scores".

One way to implement this is to make one huge tensor of for example flattened 80x45 grayscale frames at 2 fps. Then looking up part of a video is as simple as one matmul and selecting the best candidates. This way I could easily fit 10-20k videos in resident GPU memory of a medium GPU. From that point you have one or more candidates and you can further pinpoint it to the actual frame. You really need to cache the pexels originals or you will not be in time to post the video, which I would host not on cloud storage, but on the miner server itself. Plus some additional optimizations ofc.

Needless to say, this is a nice exercise in ffmpeg, optimization and such, but doesn't have _anything_ to do with the stated purpose of the subnet. But that is Bittensor lol

Of course pinpointing the exact frame is also a nice one to do on GPU, we used 160x90 grayscale for that, and calculated a matmul of flattened query video with flattened original. Then find the best diagonal to get the frame-accurate offset. Then you have to be careful to slice at the exact frame, which is a bit cumbersome with ffmpeg.

It also helps to use the exact settings and even ffmpeg and codec versions as the validator, the downside of which is that you get huge (100-400 mb) videos. Due to the nature of h264, when re-encoding, you can have slight differences where blocks of pixels may be moved in a different frame, depending on such settings. This of course hurts PieAPP and VMAF a lot. That's why running the same code matters. Also, we found even the same ffmpeg and library version behave differently on different CPUs, because different CPUs use different code paths (optimized for SSE4.x, AVX and what not).
The last few tricks we employed will be shared in an upcoming article about _the devops miner_ 😉
